		<item>
		<title>For Writer, Talent Finally Succeeds Where Chance Failed</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/ThePassiveVoice/~3/yv5aXD58YHk/</link>
		<comments>http://www.thepassivevoice.com/01/2015/for-writer-talent-finally-succeeds-where-chance-failed/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 03 Jan 2015 17:39:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Passive Guy]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Books in General]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.thepassivevoice.com/?p=59130</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[From The New York Times: BROOKLINE, Mass. — On a recent drizzly afternoon, the short-story writer Edith Pearlman sat reminiscing in the living room of her apartment here with her best friend, Sandy Siler, a retired psychoanalyst. Ms. Pearlman recalled a trip they had taken as young women to the Venice Lido. One day, while [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>From The New York Times:</p>
<blockquote>
<p id="story-continues-1" class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="208" data-total-count="208">BROOKLINE, Mass. — On a recent drizzly afternoon, the short-story writer Edith Pearlman sat reminiscing in the living room of her apartment here with her best friend, Sandy Siler, a retired psychoanalyst.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="327" data-total-count="535">Ms. Pearlman recalled a trip they had taken as young women to the Venice Lido. One day, while her friend was off swimming, Ms. Pearlman visited the casino. She said that the man who ran the roulette wheel was very kind and every so often would say something to her, loud enough so only she could hear it and know where to bet.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="88" data-total-count="623">“It was an inside job,” Ms. Pearlman said, grinning broadly. “I did very well.”</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="58" data-total-count="681">Dr. Siler chimed in, “Edie paid for her entire trip.”</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="147" data-total-count="828">It was the sort of story — a pretty young tourist, a lovesick croupier, the ineffable mechanisms of chance — in which Ms. Pearlman specializes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="147" data-total-count="828">On Tuesday, Little, Brown will release “Honeydew,” her fifth story collection and first to be published by a major house. Ms. Pearlman is enjoying a commercial breakthrough at 78, after five decades of writing short stories, some 200 of them, nearly all appearing in small literary magazines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="147" data-total-count="828">. . . .</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="279" data-total-count="2237">“Edith has always known that death is the essential human story,” the novelist Ann Patchett said. “It’s not about falling in love. It’s not about travel and expectation. The difference between her and the rest of us is that she has always had this electricity, this capacity to draw beauty from loss.”</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="279" data-total-count="2237">Ms. Pearlman emerged from obscurity in 2011 when her previous collection,“Binocular Vision,” became the first book ever to be a finalist for the National Book Award, the Story Prize, The Los Angeles Times Book Prize and the National Book Critics Circle Award, which it won.</p>
<p id="story-continues-3" class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="580" data-total-count="2817">“With Edith, so often I can’t remember if her stories are something I read or something that somebody told me,” said Ms. Patchett, who wrote the introduction to “Binocular Vision” after selecting one of Ms. Pearlman’s pieces for the “Best American Short Stories” anthology. “Often I’ll be driving and I’ll think: ‘Now, who was that woman who gave pedicures? The one who was spied on by that lonely man from his third-floor bathroom?’ Her stories are so true in how things are lived and how we tell them to one another that they become true in my mind.”</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="580" data-total-count="2817">. . . .</p>
<p id="story-continues-6" class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="219" data-total-count="4428">“I wrote in the cellar for a number of years,” Ms. Pearlman said. “I needed a private space, and it had a furnace, so it was always warm.” Her armchair was forever flanked by the books she used for her research.</p>
<p class="story-body-text story-content" data-para-count="387" data-total-count="4815">Ms. Pearlman published her first story in 1969. Her first book didn’t appear until 1996, a 27-year lag that has been a source of consternation among her fans. But she herself has long promoted writing as an amateur enterprise. All her work, she explained, is directed toward “a single imaginary ideal reader, someone wishing to be entertained and not averse to being enlightened.”</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Link to the rest at <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/03/books/edith-pearlmans-new-book-is-honeydew.html"  target="_blank" rel="nofollow">The New York Times</a></p>
